The source code is your best guide to the internals.

The now-deprecated DomainScope, HostScope, and PathScope used a list of 
acceptable URI regexes to rule things in, and performed a linear probe 
through the list until either one matched or all failed. That was 
atrociously inefficient and very slow for large seed lists.

The SURT-based scopes (deprected SurtPrefixedScope and recommended 
SurtPrefixedDecideRule) use sorted lists of acceptable SURT-form URI 
prefixes. A candidate URI is compared against the prefix immediately 
preceding it in sorted order; if the prefix matches the URI is ruled in. 
Much faster, in practice.

